	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Commission staff paper explores the implications of reform options for sugar</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 May 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>
The Commission staff paper 'Reforming the European Union's Sugar <br /> &nbsp;Policy: Summary of Impact Assessment Work', looks at:</p>
<ul>

<li>the current sugar regime;</li>

<li>the pressures for reform;</li>

<li>the guidelines for reform;</li>

<li>the four options under consideration;</li>

<li>the impact of each of the four options on different stakeholders.</li>

</ul>
<p>The four options considered are:</p>
<ul>

<li>the 'status quo' option;</li>

<li>the 'fixed quotas' option;</li>

<li>the 'fall in price' option;</li>

<li>the 'liberalisation' option.</li>

</ul>
<p>
The 'fall in price' option and 'liberalisation' option <br />
 &nbsp;are summarised as having 'very negative' or 'even dangerous' consequences <br />
 &nbsp;for ACP countries. The 'status quo' option and 'fixed quota' option <br />
 &nbsp;are seen as the preferred options for ACP countries. Of the options <br />
 &nbsp;considered the option which scores highest in terms of progress <br />
 &nbsp;towards the attainment of EU objectives is the 'fall in price' option. <br />
 &nbsp;This option also has the advantage for the EU of imposing no additional <br />
 &nbsp;budgetary costs in the early stages of implementation. Under Phase 2 of the reform process, however, some &amp;euro;1 billion a year would <br />
 &nbsp;be required to finance direct aid payments to EU sugar farmers taken <br />
 &nbsp;into the decoupled single farm payment scheme. However such funds <br />
 &nbsp;could easily be generated through extending the application of 'dynamic <br />
 &nbsp;modulation' which was accepted by EU member states in principle <br />
 &nbsp;as part of the June 2003 reform package. This option is the most <br />
 &nbsp;elaborated of the options considered in the Commission staff paper <br /> &nbsp;(see box).</p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
<tr>
<td valign="top">  <p>
Commission Scenario for the Implementation of the 'Fall <br />
 &nbsp;in Price' Option for Sugar Sector Reform<br /> <b>Phase 1: </b></p>
<ul>

<li>
 The EU sugar price would be reduced by between 15% and <br /> &nbsp;20%, reaching a price of &amp;euro;600/tonne for white sugar. </li>

<li>
 The intervention price in the sugar sector would be <br /> &nbsp;abolished.</li>

<li>
 As a consequence the preferential price for ACP sugar <br /> &nbsp;would fall to &amp;euro;435 per tonne of raw sugar. </li>

<li>
 EU sugar growers would not need to be compensated since <br />
 &nbsp;the sugar levies would be abolished, 'C' sugar production <br />
 &nbsp;would be cut and extra revenue would be generated by the <br />
 &nbsp;sale or leasing of quotas under a new quota-management <br /> &nbsp;system.</li>

<li>
 The EU may however need to provide restructuring assistance <br /> &nbsp;to traditional ACP suppliers.</li>

</ul>
<p><b>Phase 2:</b></p>
<ul>

<li>
 The Community market price for white sugar would fall <br /> &nbsp;to &amp;euro;450/ tonne, a 40% reduction overall.</li>

<li>
 Compensation would be paid to EU beet growers through <br />
 &nbsp;the decoupled farm payment system; the budget increase <br />
 &nbsp;required would ultimately be about &amp;euro;1 billion per <br /> &nbsp;annum.</li>

<li>
 EU production quotas would be cut and eventually abolished <br /> &nbsp;once the EU market has reached equilibrium.</li>

<li>The ACP sugar price would be cut again to &amp;euro;290/tonne.</li>

<li>
 Restructuring of production in ACP countries would also <br /> &nbsp;need to be financed.</li>

</ul>
<p>
<b>Outcome</b> <br />
 &nbsp;After this phased reform which would be fully in place by <br /> &nbsp;2013:</p>
<ul>

<li>
 sugar production in the EU-25 would be around 14 million <br /> &nbsp;tonnes;</li>

<li>
 preferential imports would total about 2.5 million <br /> &nbsp;tonnes;</li>

<li>EU sugar exports would virtually cease.</li>

</ul>

  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>
In terms of its impact on the ACP the 'fall in price' option would <br />
 &nbsp;result in a fall in the price offered for ACP sugar to &amp;euro;435/tonne <br />
 &nbsp;under Phase 1 and to &amp;euro;290/tonne under Phase 2 of the reform <br />
 &nbsp;as set out in the Commission staff paper's indicative scenario. <br />
 &nbsp;Commission estimates suggest that with a raw sugar price offered <br />
 &nbsp;to ACP suppliers of &amp;euro;435 per tonne the following ACP exporters <br /> &nbsp;would be likely to cease exports to the EU:</p>
<ul>

<li>Democratic Republic of the Congo</li>

<li>Jamaica</li>

<li>Madagascar. </li>

</ul>
<p>
With a raw sugar price of &amp;euro;290 per tonne the following ACP <br /> &nbsp;exporters would also be likely to cease exports to the EU:</p><table class="renderedtable" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="70%">
<tr>
<td valign="top">  
<ul>

<li>Burkina Faso;</li>

<li>Ivory Coast; </li>

<li>Congo Brazzaville;</li>

<li>Malawi;</li>

<li>Swaziland;</li>

<li>Fiji.</li>

</ul>

  </td><td valign="top">  
<ul>

<li>Tanzania; </li>

<li>Mauritius;</li>

<li>Guyana;</li>

<li>Senegal;</li>

<li>Belize;</li>

</ul>

  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>
According to Commission estimates the only ACP exporters capable <br />
 &nbsp;of continuing to supply the EU market at a price of &amp;euro;290/tonne <br />
 &nbsp;are Zimbabwe, Zambia, Sudan, Ethiopia and Mozambique. However, with <br />
 &nbsp;the EU market becoming less attractive, the volume of exports that <br />
 &nbsp;these countries would be willing to supply would be greatly reduced, <br />
 &nbsp;with Commission estimates suggesting it would amount to little more <br />
 &nbsp;than 200,000 tonnes. Commission estimates suggest that revenue losses <br />
 &nbsp;to ACP exporters would total some &amp;euro;300 million per annum. The <br />
 &nbsp;Commission staff paper acknowledges that this would require financial <br /> &nbsp;assistance to ACP producers for restructuring.</p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
<tr>
<td colspan="5" valign="top">  <b>Main Results of EU Options for Sugar Sector Reform</b>
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top">  
<b>Current Situation:</b> <br />
 &nbsp;Internal EU white sugar price<br />
 &nbsp;EU sugar production quotas<br />
 &nbsp;EU production<br />
 &nbsp;EU imports<br /> &nbsp;EU exports
  </td><td colspan="3" valign="top">  
&nbsp;&amp;euro;725 per tonne <br />
